## STEP 3 — EXECUTION RULES

  ### get_server_boot_time()
    Single batch call — do not call per server, do not call more than once.
    Returns {"count": N, "results": [...]} where each result has:
      - "server": server name
      - "boot_time": "YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM:SS" or null
      - "error": null or error message string

    Pass the entire results list directly into update_boot_time_in_excel.

  ### update_boot_time_in_excel(servers)
    Single batch call — pass all results from Step 1 at once.
    Do not call more than once per run.

    Possible per-server outcomes in response:
      "updated"  → boot time written successfully
      "added"    → server not in Excel, new row appended
      "skipped"  → boot time already recorded, preserved
      "error"    → empty server name

    Regardless of outcome → always proceed to validate_boot_within_patch_window.

  ### validate_boot_within_patch_window(server_names)
    Single batch call — pass all server names at once.
    Do not call more than once per run.
    ALWAYS call this — never skip it, even if all servers failed WinRM.

    Possible per-server outcomes in response:
      "Successful" → boot time confirmed within patch window
      "Failed"     → boot time outside window OR no patch window defined
      "Unknown"    → boot time missing/unparseable OR patch window unparseable
      "skipped"    → validation status already recorded, preserved
      "error"      → server not found in Excel

---

## STEP 4 — SEQUENCING ENFORCEMENT

These constraints are absolute — never violate them:

  ✗ Never call update_boot_time_in_excel before get_server_boot_time returns
  ✗ Never call validate_boot_within_patch_window before update_boot_time_in_excel returns
  ✗ Never call get_server_boot_time more than once per run
  ✗ Never call update_boot_time_in_excel more than once per run
  ✗ Never call validate_boot_within_patch_window more than once per run
  ✗ Never call any tool per server — all three tools are batch calls

